The project explores Sephora skincare product reviews in the United States, focusing on two research questions. First, we identify the most frequently mentioned attributes in customer reviews through sentiment analysis and text mining. Second, we investigate customer preferences among different skin-tone subgroups. By categorizing reviews based on sentiments and attributes for each subgroup, we are able to gain insights into customer perceptions and preferences. This analysis empowers Sephora to make data-driven decisions to tailor marketing strategies to specific customer segments.

Clean Data

Transform skin_tone into Categories

Since there are too many types of skin tones, we decide to group the 13 types of skin tones into 3 main categories: light (light, fair, fairLight, porelain), medium (lightMedium, medium, mediumTan, olive), and tan (tan, deep, rich, dark, ebony) for our further analysis.

library(dplyr)

# Create a mapping of each skin tone to 3 main categories
skin_tone_mapping = list(
  light = c("light", "fair", "fairLight", "porcelain"),
  medium = c("lightMedium", "medium", "mediumTan", "olive"),
  tan = c("tan", "deep", "rich", "dark", "ebony")
)

# Create a function to map each skin tones to 3 main categories
map_skin_tone = function(skin_tone) {
  main_category = NA
  for (category in names(skin_tone_mapping)) {
    if (skin_tone %in% skin_tone_mapping[[category]]) {
      main_category <- category
      break
    }
  }
  return(main_category)
}

# Apply the mapping to create a new column with main categories
review_clean = review_clean %>%
  mutate(skin_tone_cat = sapply(skin_tone, map_skin_tone)) %>%
  select(author_id, review_text, skin_tone_cat)

head(review_clean)

Conduct Text Mining on All review_text

# Tokenize review_text
library(dplyr); library(tidytext)

Based on our literature review, we know that the 4 main attributes that customers care the most when purchasing products are price, quality (including product smell, texture, functionality, and etc.), package design, and ingredient.

We group the most frequently mentioned words in both positive and negative reviews into these 4 categories. If the word doesnt fit into any category, it would be put into the others categories.

# Create a mapping of words to categories
word_category_mapping = data.frame(
  word = c("smell", "smells", "greasy", "break", "sticky",
           "bad", "dark", "expensive", "irritate", "hard",
           "wrinkles", "irritation", "harsh", "pricey", "issues",
           "broke", "disappointed", "scars", "bumps", "irritated",
           "love", "recommend", "amazing", "sensitive", "soft",
           "nice", "smooth", "super", "free", "clean",
           "glow", "worth", "perfect", "complimentary", "fresh",
           "gentle", "pretty", "helped", "loved", "fine"),
  category = c("quality", "quality", "quality", "quality", "quality",
               "quality", "others", "price", "others", "others",
               "quality", "others", "quality", "quality", "others",
               "others", "others", "quality", "quality", "others",
               "others", "others", "others", "quality", "quality",
               "others", "quality", "others", "price", "quality",
               "quality", "price", "others", "price", "quality",
               "quality", "package_design", "quality", "others", "others")
  )

# Merge the data frames to add the 'category' column to the original data (for positive reviews)
pos_word_freq = pos_word %>%
  left_join(word_category_mapping, by = "word") %>%
  group_by(category) %>%
  summarize(pos_review_count = sum(positive)) %>%
  arrange(desc(pos_review_count))

pos_word_freq
# Merge the data frames to add the 'category' column to the original data (for negative reviews)
neg_word_freq = neg_word %>%
  left_join(word_category_mapping, by = "word") %>%
    group_by(category) %>%
    summarize(neg_review_count = sum(negative)) %>%
    arrange(desc(neg_review_count))

neg_word_freq

Result

Lets use chi-square test to measure if the counts in quality category is significantly different from others.

The null hypothesis (H0) for the chi-square test is that there is no significant difference in the counts of quality and other categories. The alternative hypothesis (Ha) is that there is a significant difference.

As the chi-square test results shown blow, both p-values are less than 0.05, indicating the word counts in quality category are significantly different from other categories, regardless of positive or negative reviews.

library(stats)

# for "quality" category in the positive reviews
chisq.test(pos_word_freq$pos_review_count)
## 
##  Chi-squared test for given probabilities
## 
## data:  pos_word_freq$pos_review_count
## X-squared = 569313, df = 3, p-value < 2.2e-16
# for "quality" category in the negative reviews
chisq.test(neg_word_freq$neg_review_count)
## 
##  Chi-squared test for given probabilities
## 
## data:  neg_word_freq$neg_review_count
## X-squared = 213750, df = 2, p-value < 2.2e-16
# Visualize the Attribute Distribution (for positive reviews)
pos_word_freq$category = factor(pos_word_freq$category,
                                levels = pos_word_freq$category[order(-pos_word_freq$pos_review_count)])

ggplot(pos_word_freq, aes(x = category, y = pos_review_count, fill = category)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity")

# Visualize the Attribute Distribution (for negative reviews)
neg_word_freq$category = factor(neg_word_freq$category,
                                levels = neg_word_freq$category[order(-neg_word_freq$neg_review_count)])

ggplot(neg_word_freq, aes(x = category, y = neg_review_count, fill = category)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity")

  summarize(pos_review_count = sum(positive)) %>%

  geom_bar(stat = "identity")

Result

We are using chi-square test for independence to measure whether there is a significant difference in word category distribution between customers with different skin tones.

Since the p-value we got from chi-square test is > 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis, indicating that there is no evidence to suggest that the word category proportions are significantly different across skin-tone groups.

# combine positive and negative word count tables into one dataframe for each skin-tone group (light, medium, tan)

  full_join(pos_word_light, neg_word_light, by = "category", suffixes = c("_pos", "_neg"))
